We returned to Dong A tonight after a five year absence ... and was immediately, but pleasantly, shocked to hear that the owner and his wife still remembered us ... to the point of knowing, even before we said anything, what we wanted!
(Which says volumes about our consistency when it comes to food, I guess).
Why did we stop coming to Dong A?
Well, five years ago, they didn't take credit cards; we had discovered Da Vang and we just got tired of going to this place all the time (on average, every week, at least once ... and we live 20+ miles away one way).
Fortunately, they take VISA now; but they're still far away.
Dong A should be getting much more business than they do and, unfortunately, a good part of the reason they don't is location, location, location.
They're not in a good neighborhood and they've got competition not too far away.
But it's the neighborhood that's the problem:  a lot of people aren't going to venture into this part of town and the locals, who live nearby, frankly either don't have the money to partake in "exotic" food or the interest.
While it's true, that the pho here is not the best, unlike most Vietnamese restaurants in the Valley, there is a large variety of dishes here and ... hooray, hooray ... not based solely on pho, which is almost always the mainstay in other Viet restaurants.
Our personal favorites -- as obvious from the fact, that, after five years, we didn't need to remind them what we wanted -- are the goi cuon and the spicy chicken/beef with eggplant.
I always end up with a big bill here, not because prices are unreasonable --- they're not --- but because I usually take home 5 or so orders or goi cuon  ($6.00 each for four rolls).
Why the need to take home the extra rolls?
Because even though we have local Vietnamese restaurants here, no one makes goi cuon like they do:  large, crispy, tasty, fresh.
I can't describe it any better:  go and try it yourselves.
The cha gio are small, but at $1.75 for two pieces, why are you whining?
The chicken or beef with eggplant is a different and tasty --- not to mention "welcome" --- change to the typical and predictable cuisine you find in other Vietnamese restaurants (and is far from being the only unique, non-pho dish).
Yes, it is very oily; but you don't have to eat the spicy oil ... that's your choice.
Don't worry about it coating and making the meat and eggplant greasy:  for whatever reason, it doesn't.
The other downside of the restaurant is a non-functioning -- or under-functioning(?
) -- air conditioner.
There are enough fans in there to keep it reasonably comfortable, even in the Summer; but beware the rare, humid, monsoon nights  (and guess how the weather was tonight, when we went!)!
The decor is extraordinarily basic; but show me a Vietnamese restaurant, where you remember how the restaurant looked!
Service is personable and friendly.
Yes, they're slow; however, it's the husband and wife, and that's it.
That's one reason why I actually tipped the portion of our order we were taking home as an extra:  normally, I wouldn't; but they make everything on the spot and let me tell you:  five orders of goi cuon, at four rolls per order, takes a long time!
Have patience!
It's absolutely worth it.
If you're in the neighborhood --- and even if you aren't --- and want to try some atypical Vietnamese food at reasonable prices and outstanding taste, ignore the superficial disadvantages and come eat here!
You'll be glad you did.
WISHLIST:  while not much of a money-maker, I wish they made sandwiches; a personal favorite of mine in Vietnamese restaurants.
I have a strong suspicion, they'd be very good here, based on how they make the appetizers.

